Finance and Employment / Employment




 













Michael D. Capellas


Career PathLight Reading12/10/2002Comment (5)Login50%50%


Tweet










Michael D. Capellas has taken on what could be the role of a lifetime.

At 48 he has held more than two dozen jobs at eight companies, including Schlumberger Ltd., SAP America Inc., Oracle Corp. (Nasdaq: ORCL), Compaq, and, briefly, Hewlett-Packard Co. (NYSE: HPQ). In mid-November he accepted the offer to become chairman and CEO of bankrupt carrier WorldCom Inc. (OTC: WCOEQ).
Capellas's resumé speaks volumes about his restless ambition. He was once quoted as saying, “I always wanted the toughest job." 

With that in mind, Capellas would be hard pressed to find a harder job than the one he has just taken on. Although WorldCom still hails as the nation's No. 2 long-distance communications company and one of the world's largest Internet carriers, it has been tainted by scandal and buried in bankruptcy.  And like the rest of the telecommunications market, it is struggling to stay alive. 
Although Capellas has not had any traditional telecom experience, he has gained a reputation as an astute manager. Most recently he served as president of Hewlett-Packard. And before that he was chairman and CEO of Compaq, where he helped broker the 2001 merger between Compaq and HP. He joined Compaq in 1998 as chief information officer and also served as chief operating officer before being named CEO in July 1999.  Prior to his Compaq days, Capellas held senior positions at SAP America and Oracle Corp. in areas ranging from application development to sales and general management. He also spent 16 years with Schlumberger, a global technology service provider, in management positions around the world.
Several industry observers say they think Capellas is a good choice for WorldCom.

 "A high-profile CEO certainly increases the odds of the company emerging from bankruptcy,” says John Hodulik, an analyst with UBS Warburg. “I would say this is a good sign for them." 

Unlike former WorldCom CEO Bernard Ebbers, whose aggressive acquisition strategy has received much of the blame for the accounting scandals surrounding the carrier, Capellas is viewed as a conservative, cautious strategist. He is credited with bringing stability, if not massive growth, to Compaq after he took over the company in 1999. 

 “Getting someone with a conservative approach might be the best move in the world right now,” says Frank Dzubeck, president of Communications Network Architects. “He’d be a good one for the job." 

Capellas will certainly have his work cut out for him. The company has admitted that its earnings misstatements for the past couple of years total more than $9 billion, and most observers expect even more accounting problems to come out of the woodwork in coming months (see WorldCom Restatements Top $9B).

WorldCom says it plans to pay its new chairman and CEO a salary of $5 million for his first year on the job. This includes a $1.5 million base salary along with a $2 million signing bonus and other  potential performance bonuses worth $1.5 million, according to bankruptcy filings. Capellas will also get another $18 million in restricted stock in the newly reorganized WorldCom when it emerges from bankruptcy. The company expects to come out of bankruptcy in mid-2003.

The proposed WorldCom package would be a nice bump up from Capellas's former job. According to a Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) filing, Capellas’s annual salary for 2001 was $1.6 million, and he received $2.1 million in other compensation.  

As of last year, former WorldCom CEO Ebbers reportedly made $1 million in base salary. He recieved a $10 million bonus in 2000 and still owes the company more than $400 million in loans.

The compensation package still needs to be approved by the bankruptcy court and pass the scrutiny of the court-appointed monitor, Richard Breeden. A hearing to review Capellas' pay package will be held on Dec. 16.

Capellas, who had his first official day on the job in early December, has chosen to work out of the company’s  Ashburn, Va., office instead of its headquarters in Clinton, Miss.

— Eugénie Larson, Reporter, and Marguerite Reardon, Senior Editor, Light Reading





